<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Fires are variable in space and time across the distribution of this alliance. In annual herb types such as this alliance, fires result in a short-term increase in available nitrogen and phosphorus (Menke and Rice 1981). Because fine stems generally create lower-intensity fires, little heat is transported more than a few centimeters into the soil, and seeds in the soil are generally unaffected. Keeley (2002a) suggested that fires occurred in higher frequency adjacent to long-term human occupation sites, and Anderson (2005) suggested that many annual plants and associated geophytes benefited from tending by Native Americans. As noted by Parish (1907), an extensive fire occurred in 1903 over the ridges south and southwest of Los Gatos, after which patches of <i>Monolopia gracilens </i>and other annuals were abundant post-fire for three years, and  then not seen in large extent afterwards. Similarly, after the extensive Morgan fire on Mount Diablo, Bartosh and Peterson (2016) found significant abundance of forbs such as <i>M. gracilens </i> for two years afterwards, with their richness and abudance waning a few years post-fire.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
