    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Ag). Patchy stands with <i>Monolopia major</i> as a co-dominant occur at Black Diamond Mines Regional Park and the Livermore Valley area.  Intermittent stands with <i>Monolopia gracilens </i> occur in post-fire sites on Mount Diablo, on ridges of the Santa Cruz Mountains near Los Gatos, and in adjacent areas of the South Bay Region on serpentines (H. Bartosh, pers. comm., 2018)  . More sampling and analysis are needed to substantiate associations and their relationships to this and other herbaceous alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad-e, Ag-k). Stands occur across the section, including in the Carrizo Plain, Caliente and Temblor Ranges, Paso Robles hills and valley, south eastern Interior Santa Lucia Range, Ciervo Hills, Panoche Hills, Corral Hollow, and near Livermore including <i>Monolopia lanceolata</i> and <i>Monolopia major</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, Ax, Az). Stands occur in the southern and western San Joaquin Valley including in the Tejon Hills, Comanche Hills, and north to the eastern edges of the Mount Hamilton Range and Mount Diablo with stands of <i>Coreopsis calliopsidea, Monolopia lanceolata, Monolopia major</i>, and/or <i>M. stricta</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag). Stands of <i>Coreopsis calliopsidea </i> occur in the western Mojave including near Mojave, Kramer Junction, Kramer Hills and elsewhere, and stands of <i>C. bigelovii</i> occur near Fremont Valley. More sampling is needed to determine full extent of this alliance in this ecoregion.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands of <i>Monolopia lanceolata </i> occur in the the southern most Sierra Nevada in Tejon Ranch.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands occur in the southern Sierra Nevada foothills including at Tejon Ranch, Tehachapi foothills, and in the lower San Emigdio Mountains such as in Windwolves Preserve, including stands of <i>Coreopsis calliopsidea, Monolopia lanceolata</i> and <i>M. major</i>. Stands with <i>Coreopsis stillmanii</i> occur on serpentinite in the central foothills; more sampling and analysis is needed in this ecoregion to determine associations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb). Stands of <i>Coreopsis calliopsidea </i>  and <i>Monolopia lanceolata</i> occur in the northern part of this section.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands with monolopia and related annual herbs vary in space and time, depending on rainfall, fire, and other disturbance. Grazing at low stocking rates is not detrimental. </div>
</div>

    

    

